Defence Minister Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula paid tribute to her late father by taking to the stage and singing.  Dressed in a satin  purple gown, she mesmerised mourners as she sang the famous medley “Swing Low Sweet Chariot” at the funeral in East London. In her company was the Sweet Voices of Africa Ensemble male band from Mdantsane. Her father Douglas Vakele  Mapisa died two weeks ago after suffering prostrate cancer. Among the mourners were high-profile politicians and business people including Bantu Holomisa, Gugile Nkwinti, Mcebisi Skwatsha, Noxolo Kieviet and Xola Pakati. Social Development Minister Bathabile Dlamini walked in with Buffalo City Metro mayor Xola Pakati. Defence and Military Veterans Minister Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula’s father will be laid to rest next Thursday in East London. The funeral service of the minister’s father, Douglas Mapisa, will be held at Abbotsford Christian Centre from 9am. The 96-year-old died on Sunday after a long illness at Cecilia Makiwane Hospital. Family… December 9, 2017 A Mercedes-Benz sedan belonging to Defence Minister Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula is scheduled to be auctioned on September 14. She has failed since last year to settle a R50000 debt to a King William’s Town garage which worked on her faulty engine. The 1998 C180 Mercedes, used by the minister’s 96-year-old father,… September 6, 2017 The Democratic Alliance (DA) said it will be laying charges against Defence and Military Veterans Minister Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula for violating the Immigration Act. The minister allegedly smuggled her late son’s alleged girlfriend‚ Michelle Wege‚ into South Africa on an air force jet. Th charges are in addition to the request… May 30, 2016